13. Conceptual Summary

TERA assumes that real spaces are never perfectly hermetic.

Instead, spaces exchange information through oscillatory interactions.

Stability arises when:

resonance aligns information transfer

damping limits uncontrolled drift

decision gates regulate state transitions


The result is a controlled evolution of information and energy across time.



TERA — Axis Derivation and Master Equation

1. Fundamental Observation

Real systems are not hermetic.

Any physical or informational space exchanges:

signals

energy

disturbances


with its environment.

Therefore every system evolves as an open dynamic space.


---

2. Two Interacting Spaces

TERA models reality as interaction between two spaces:

A(t) = \text{perception space}

B(t) = \text{model space}

The informational difference between them is

C(t) = B(t) - A(t)

This difference represents informational drift.


---

3. Time Axis

Time evolves as

t \rightarrow t + \Delta t

and therefore system states evolve as

S(t+\Delta t)

Time introduces the possibility of change and drift.


---

4. Information Axis

Information represents structured state description.

I(t)

Information flows between spaces through signals and observations.

This flow is never perfect, producing drift

C(t) \neq 0


---

5. Energy Axis

Information transfer requires energy.

Let

E(t)

represent the available energy for state change.

Energy determines the amplitude of correction.


---

6. Resonance / Temporal Axis

Information exchange between spaces often occurs through oscillatory signals.

We describe this through frequency

\omega

Example disturbance

w(t) = a\sin(\omega t + \phi)

Resonance therefore defines when corrections interact constructively or destructively.


---

7. The Four Axes of TERA

Combining the previous sections gives four fundamental axes:

(I, E, \omega, t)

These correspond to

Information
Energy
Resonance / Frequency
Time

Geometrically this produces a tetrahedral relation.

Each axis interacts with the others.


---

8. State Space

The system state is

S(t)

and evolves through time according to interactions of the four axes.

State drift is determined by the difference space

C(t) = B(t) - A(t)


---

9. Stability Condition

Define a Lyapunov function

V(t) = ||C(t)||^2

The system is stable when

\Delta V(t) \le 0

meaning the difference between model and perception does not grow.


---

10. Control Requirement

Because open systems experience disturbances

w(t) \neq 0

a correction mechanism is required.

Let

u(t)

represent the system correction.


---

11. Gate Logic

TERA introduces a discrete decision gate

ACCEPT
WAIT
REJECT

based on system stress

s(p)

Decision rule

ACCEPT  if s(p) < ε
WAIT    if ds/dt ≈ 0
REJECT  if s(p) ≥ ε


---

